2.Controls

Kate Bowie, PhD and Lisa Karstens, PhD

2025-03-07

Purpose

This RMD is all about creating the ps object and evaluating controls. It includes: * Includes creating the ps object from the CSVs * Assigning disease to samples * Evaluating reads (abundance and length) * Examining positive and negative controls * Removing contamination

rownames(asv_table) <- asv_table[,1]

meta <- meta %>% 
  select(-"...1", -"...2")

Create ps object

otu_data <- otu_table(asv_table, taxa_are_rows = FALSE)
sample_data <- sample_data(meta)
tax_data   <- tax_table(tax_table)

ps_orig <- phyloseq(otu_data, sample_data, tax_data)

tax_ps <- as.matrix(ps_orig@tax_table) 

rm(asv_table, tax_table)

Seperate mock community samples

meta$patient_ID[meta$fraction == "mock_community"] <- paste0(meta$replicate[meta$fraction == "mock_community"], "_", meta$extraction_batch[meta$fraction == "mock_community"])

meta$extraction <- "NA"

meta$extraction[meta$fraction == "mock_community"] <- meta$extraction_batch[meta$fraction == "mock_community"]

sample_data(ps_orig) <- meta

Combining samples

As noted previously, all samples were processed in triplicate. As blood is low microbial biomass, we thought the 200 µL samples would not adequately capture the composition. Therefore, the replicates for each sequencing sample were combined prior to rarefaction to represent one microbiome composition per fraction per individual.

ps_df <- psmelt(ps_orig)

ps_df <- ps_df %>% 
  group_by(fraction, patient_ID, dnase, OTU) %>% 
  summarise(tot_abundance = sum(Abundance))


# create new sample names
ps_df <- ps_df %>% 
  mutate(sam_names = paste0(fraction, "_", patient_ID, "_", dnase))

Make combined OTU table

otu_ps <- ps_df %>% 
  select(sam_names, OTU, tot_abundance) %>% 
  pivot_wider(names_from = OTU, values_from = tot_abundance, id_cols = sam_names) %>% 
  data.frame()
## Adding missing grouping variables: `fraction`, `patient_ID`, `dnase`
rownames(otu_ps) <- otu_ps$sam_names
otu_ps <- otu_ps %>%
  select(-sam_names) %>% 
  as.matrix()

Adding back in meta data

meta_combo <- meta %>% 
  select(patient_ID, fraction, dnase, is.neg, PSA, BMI, age, extraction)

meta <- meta_combo %>% 
  mutate(sam_names = paste0(fraction, "_", patient_ID, "_", dnase)) %>% 
  unique()

rownames(meta) <- meta$sam_names

Create combined ps object

ps <- phyloseq(otu_table(otu_ps, taxa_are_rows = FALSE), tax_table(tax_ps), sample_data(meta))

rm(tax_ps, otu_ps, ps_df, meta_combo)

## Add disease

meta_ps <- meta %>% 
mutate(disease = case_when(
patient_ID %in% c(1,8,10,14,15) ~ "low-grade",
patient_ID %in% c(4,5,9,11,12) ~ "high-grade",
patient_ID %in% c(2,3,6,13,16) ~ "screen-negative",
TRUE ~ patient_ID,
))

sample_data(ps) <- meta_ps

Filtering by sequence quality

Read length

First let’s take a look at the length. Full-length 16S rRNA gene should be around 1500 bp. We have a lot of short sequences that we aren’t confident in and will filter out.

histogram(nchar(taxa_names(ps)), breaks = 30, , xlab="Sequence Length (bp)")

Sequences 1350 < x < 1600

As we’re focusing only on sequences we have full confidence in, we will continue our analyses with only sequences between 1350 and 1600 bp.

taxa_to_keep <- data.frame(taxa_id = taxa_names(ps), seq_long = nchar(taxa_names(ps)) > 1350 & nchar(taxa_names(ps)) < 1600)

taxa_to_keep <- taxa_to_keep %>% 
  filter(seq_long == TRUE)

ps_long <- subset_taxa(ps, taxa_names(ps) %in% taxa_to_keep$taxa_id)

# checking
histogram(nchar(taxa_names(ps_long)))

Filtering to Family

We only want sequences that we have high confidence in, therefore we have decided to only use sequences that at least have resolution to the Family level. Before filtering, 48896 ASVs. Afterwards, 38,939

ps <- ps_long %>% 
  subset_taxa(., !(is.na(Family)))

Sample reads overview

sample_data(ps_long)$SampleSums <- sample_sums(ps_long)
meta <- data.frame(ps_long@sam_data)

Negative controls

3 of my 23 negative controls failed sequencing. There is a negative for each sample type (plasma, RBC, BF, and WB). Similar to the blood fractions, all negatives for each fraction were run in triplicate. This means that each negative here is a combination of 3 samples, which is why the reads is higher than expected.

ps_neg <- subset_samples(ps, is.neg == "yes")
ps_neg <- subset_taxa(ps_neg, taxa_sums(ps_neg) > 0)
sample_data(ps_neg)$SampleSums <- sample_sums(ps_neg)
meta_neg <- data.frame(ps_neg@sam_data)

meta_neg %>% 
  summarise(avg_reads = mean(SampleSums), min_ss = min(SampleSums), max_ss = max(SampleSums))

Removing geuns Prauserella and Rubrobacter
